A South African Breweries (SAB) truck leaves the Newlands Brewery in Cape Town. JOHANNESBURG - South African Breweries has confirmed it's pulling investments worth another R2.5-billion from the country. This follows government's third alcohol sales ban in the wake of another COVID-19 surge. The brewer, owned by AB InBev, withdrew a similar amount of spending last year after a 12-week sales ban. READ: SA Lockdown: Liquor industry calls for another tax break The latest amount withdrawn was intended for infrastructure and new equipment and brings the cut in investment by SAB to R5-billion over the last year. SAB is taking government to court to challenge the constitutionality of the third ban.  SAB - SAB Cancels Another R2.5bn in Capital Investment by eNCA.com on Scribd 